<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1325,908,1614]" box="[264,355,908,933]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis box="[264,355,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">Biology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1325,908,1614]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">
The females of 
<taxonomicName box="[493,610,948,973]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Trimeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[493,610,948,973]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">T. robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[616,679,948,974]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
were collected on flowers of an unidentified species of 
<taxonomicName box="[264,376,988,1013]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Waltheria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,376,988,1013]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">Waltheria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[400,559,988,1014]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sterculiaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="family">Sterculiaceae</taxonomicName>
) growing in abandoned pasture land. This region in northern Minas Gerais is within the southern limit of the caatinga domain, the xeric plant formation occupying most of northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[641,717,1068,1094]" name="Brazil" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1325,908,1614]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">
Four nests were found along a dirt road not far from where the females were collected. Three of them formed a loose aggregation (the entrances were 
<quantity box="[998,1137,1148,1174]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" unit="cm" value="12.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="10.0">10 to 15 cm</quantity>
apart). The soil in the area was very sandy with some intermixed clay. The entrances were provided with a short vertical mud turret of about 
<quantity box="[668,814,1228,1254]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="1.75" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.5">1.5 to 2 mm</quantity>
in height and 
<quantity box="[987,1079,1228,1254]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
in external diameter (wall about 
<quantity box="[404,493,1268,1294]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="0.9">0.9 mm</quantity>
thick). The main burrow was a vertical tunnel about 
<quantity box="[1113,1252,1268,1294]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" unit="cm" value="22.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="20.0">20 to 25 cm</quantity>
deep; no lateral shafts were excavated. Its diameter was similar to the inner diameter of the turret (
<quantity box="[272,369,1348,1374]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="3.6">3.6 mm</quantity>
). The nests contained only two contiguous cells, inclined about 
<number box="[1120,1153,1348,1374]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" value="45.0">45</number>
°, at the end of the main burrow (
<figureCitation box="[481,628,1388,1414]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 15. 10" captionStartId="4.[264,383,1204,1228]" captionTargetBox="[287,1300,326,1180]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[287,1301,326,1180]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 15. 10, Trimeria robusta n. sp. (holotype female), suctellum in dorsal view. 11) T. rubra n. sp. (holotype female), scutellum in dorsal view. 12, T. rubra n. sp. (holotype female), hind tibia. 13 – 15, T. robusta n. sp., nest detail showing the main burrow and cells. Scale bars for figures 10 – 12: 1 mm. Scale bars for figures 13 – 15: 10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172253/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">Figs. 13, 15</figureCitation>
). The cells were elongate, suboval, with the inner surface smooth and polished (
<quantity box="[528,679,1428,1454]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.565" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.43" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="15.65" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="14.3">14.3–17 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity box="[801,922,1428,1454]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="4.4" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="5.2" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.4">4.4–6 mm</quantity>
in its greater diameter) (
<figureCitation box="[1220,1310,1428,1454]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 15. 10" captionStartId="4.[264,383,1204,1228]" captionTargetBox="[287,1300,326,1180]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[287,1301,326,1180]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 15. 10, Trimeria robusta n. sp. (holotype female), suctellum in dorsal view. 11) T. rubra n. sp. (holotype female), scutellum in dorsal view. 12, T. rubra n. sp. (holotype female), hind tibia. 13 – 15, T. robusta n. sp., nest detail showing the main burrow and cells. Scale bars for figures 10 – 12: 1 mm. Scale bars for figures 13 – 15: 10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172253/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">
Fig. 
<number box="[1277,1310,1428,1454]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
). The cell walls were built with plastered mud and were about 
<quantity box="[981,1137,1468,1494]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.25" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="0.725" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.65">0.65–0.8 mm</quantity>
thick.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1325,908,1614]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">
Little is known about the nesting biology of the species of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1127,1228,1508,1533]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Trimeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1127,1228,1508,1533]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">Trimeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mechi" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" refString="Mechi, M. R. (1999 a) Nesting behavior and distribution of nests in the pollen-wasp Trimeria howardi (Masarinae, Vespoidea). Naturalia, 24, 75 - 90." type="journal article" year="1999" yearSuffix="a">
Mechi 
<number box="[264,325,1548,1574]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" value="1999.0">1999</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mechi" box="[352,511,1548,1574]" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" refString="Mechi, M. R. (1999 b) Activity cycle of the pollen wasp, Trimeria howardi (Hymenoptera: Vespidae) in Southeastern Brazil. Revista de Biologia Tropical, 47, 938948." type="journal article" year="1999" yearSuffix="b">
Mechi 
<number box="[434,495,1548,1574]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" value="1999.0">1999</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Neff" box="[524,789,1548,1574]" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" refString="Neff, J. L. &amp; Simpson, B. B. (1985) Hooked setae and narrow tubes: foretarsal pollen collection by Trimeria buyssoni (Hymenoptera: Masaridae). Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 58 (4), 730 - 732." type="journal article" year="1985">
Neff &amp; Simpson 
<number box="[727,789,1548,1574]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" value="1985.0">1985</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Zucchi" box="[801,1022,1548,1574]" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" refString="Zucchi, R.; Yamane, S. &amp; Sakagami, S. F. (1976) Preliminary notes on the habits of Trimeria howardi, a Neotropical communal masarid wasp, with description of the mature larva (Hymenoptera: Vespoidea). Insecta Matsumurana, 8, 47 - 57." type="journal article" year="1976">
Zucchi 
<emphasis box="[892,944,1548,1573]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[959,1022,1548,1574]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" value="1976.0">1976</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The nest architecture of 
<taxonomicName box="[264,380,1588,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Trimeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[264,380,1588,1613]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="66">T. robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[389,451,1588,1614]" pageId="5" pageNumber="66" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
agrees with the general pattern known for other species in the genus.
</paragraph>
